          <aside class="notes">
            The widespread use of digital electronic computing for engineering and scientific purpose began with the advent of the mainframe in the 1950s. These early systems had huge, complex hardware challenges and needed a cold, dry and secure operating environment. The multiple interconnecting devices and extensive cabling required elevated floors and many precious square metres of prime real estate to house these rooms. The operation of a single mainframe computer used colossal amounts of power and cooling.
